I think a lot about the fact that the Millennials were the last generation that could build relationships with artists without being expected to also see them critically.
We grew up in a golden age of media, with a collective consciousness for pop culture that no longer exists.
We could just dive into things without having to think about where they came from, because you couldn't figure that out back then anyway.
We didn't question the pedestal we placed her on. These parasocial relationships were so important and have influenced our lives.
That's why we have such a strong inclination towards nostalgia.
When "The Office" was still on, my friends and I used to order pizza every Thursday and watch the series together.
That was entirely different from today with streaming, where 12 episodes come out at once and everyone watches when they feel like it, and social media posts are often tagged with "spoiler warnings" or discussed in closed groups.
Deep down, we yearn for this universal community that once dominated everything.
That's why so many of us still watch outrageous series like "The Office" or movies like "Anchorman" in which so many one-liners appeared that would be memes today.
We have brought all these sayings and assumed that most of them already understand.
Today one can no longer assume that everyone knows it, even if it massively goes viral.
There's too much, and there's no way to systematize it. Whether we'll even get out of this overstimulation again.
We are trapped in a vicious cycle of discovering new content, only to realize that the artist is greedy or a hypocrite.
That's why we have to hold on to our nostalgia and at the same time accept that the people who created the works that we like can also make great mistakes.
We enter parasocial relationships with greater caution.
It is clear to us that it is difficult to become rich and powerful without stepping on the feet of one or the other along the way.
As we have lost our collective consciousness regarding the media, we have developed a class consciousness that promotes our critical thinking.
There are still some among us who lift someone up onto a pedestal, just to be shocked when they fall off.
We are in a phase of transition and I'm curious to see where it will ultimately lead.
Inclusion and safety should be the norm.
